See also: [Core Curriculum (Columbia College)](/Core_Curriculum_(Columbia_College))

Students at [Shimer College](/Shimer_College) engage in discussions of texts central to the school's core curriculum.

At the [undergraduate](/Undergraduate) level, individual [college](/College) and [university](/University) administrations and faculties sometimes mandate core curricula, particularly within the [liberal arts](/Liberal_arts). However, due to the increasing specialization and depth required in a student's major field of study, a typical core curriculum in [higher education](/Higher_education) accounts for a significantly smaller proportion of a student's coursework compared to the requirements of a [high school](/High_school) or [elementary school](/Elementary_school) core curriculum. &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93;

Among the most well-known and extensive core curriculum programs at leading American colleges and universities are those at [Columbia University](/Core_Curriculum_(Columbia_College)) and the [University of Chicago](/University_of_Chicago). Both can require up to two years of study without [advanced standing](/Advanced_standing) and are designed to cultivate critical skills across a broad spectrum of academic disciplines, including social sciences, humanities, physical and biological sciences, mathematics, writing, and foreign languages. &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93;

In 1999, the [University of Chicago](/University_of_Chicago) announced plans to reduce and modify the content of its core curriculum, decreasing the number of required courses from 21 to 15 and offering a wider range of content options. This decision garnered significant attention from major news outlets like *[The New York Times](/The_New_York_Times)* and *[The Economist](/The_Economist)*, making the university a focal point of a national debate on education. University administrators, notably then-President [Hugo F. Sonnenschein](/Hugo_F._Sonnenschein), argued that reducing the core curriculum had become both a financial and educational necessity, as the university faced challenges in attracting a comparable volume of undergraduate applicants compared to peer institutions, largely attributed to what proponents of the change perceived as a negative reaction from "the average eighteen-year-old" to the extensive core requirements. &#91;46&#93;

As core curricula began to diminish in prominence throughout the 20th century at many American institutions, some smaller colleges gained renown for embracing a core curriculum that encompassed nearly the entirety of a student's undergraduate education. These programs often utilized classic texts from the [western canon](/Western_canon) as the basis for teaching all subjects, including science. Five [Great Books](/Great_Books) colleges in the United States follow this pedagogical approach: [St. John's](/St._John%27s_College_(Annapolis/Santa_Fe)), [Shimer](/Shimer_College), [Thomas Aquinas](/Thomas_Aquinas_College), [Gutenberg College](/Gutenberg_College), and [Thomas More](/Thomas_More_College_of_Liberal_Arts). &#91;47&#93;

See also: [Association for Core Texts and Courses](/Association_for_Core_Texts_and_Courses)

##### Distribution Requirements

Some colleges adopt a middle-ground approach between highly specified and entirely unspecified curricula by implementing a system of distribution requirements. In this model, students are obligated to take courses within particular [fields of learning](/Academic_fields), but they retain the freedom to select the specific courses within those fields. &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93;

##### Open Curriculum

[Brown University](/Brown_University) celebrated the 50th anniversary of its [Open Curriculum](/Open_Curriculum_(Brown_University)) in 2019.

Other institutions have largely abandoned core requirements altogether. [Brown University](/Brown_University), for instance, offers its ["Open Curriculum"](/Open_Curriculum_(Brown_University)), established after a student-led reform movement in 1969. This system permits students to enroll in courses without adhering to any requirements beyond those specific to their chosen concentrations (majors), plus two mandatory writing courses. Consequently, it is possible for students to graduate without having taken college-level science or math courses, or conversely, to exclusively pursue science or math coursework. [Amherst College](/Amherst_College) mandates that students take one of a selection of first-year seminars but imposes no other required classes or distribution requirements. Similarly, [Grinnell College](/Grinnell_College) requires students to participate in a First-Year Tutorial during their initial semester, with no further course or distribution requirements. Other institutions with similar models include [Evergreen State College](/Evergreen_State_College), [Hamilton College](/Hamilton_College_(New_York)), and [Smith College](/Smith_College). &#91;48&#93;

[Wesleyan University](/Wesleyan_University) is another institution that does not mandate specific distribution of courses. However, Wesleyan does articulate "General Education Expectations," and failure to meet these expectations can preclude a student from receiving academic honors upon graduation. &#91;49&#93;

#### Gender Inequality in Curricula

Main article: [Gender inequality in curricula](/Gender_inequality_in_curricula)

[Gender inequality](/Gender_inequality) within curricula manifests as unequal treatment of men and women in various educational programs. Specifically, gender disparities are observable in the curricula of both schools and Teacher Education Institutes (TEIs). [Physical education](/Physical_education) (PE) serves as a prime example where issues of gender equality are highlighted due to ingrained [stereotyping](/Gender_stereotyping) of boys and girls. The prevalent belief is that boys inherently possess greater aptitude for physical activities than girls, while girls are considered more adept at domestic tasks like sewing and cooking. This is a pervasive issue across many cultures globally, not confined to a single society. &#91;50&#93;

